Cell[TextData[{
 "In the chemistry context molecular point groups represent a convenient way \
to describe molecular symmetries. The molecular point group consists of all \
rotations and reflections that do not generate any new molecular \
conformations when applied to a molecular. \n\nIn general, it is not always \
immediately obvious how to relate three-dimensional rotations and reflections \
(the molecular point  group) to the symmetry group of the Hamiltonian \
(operations that leave the Hamiltonian unchanged). From a spin dynamical \
point of view it is therefore more convenient to work with ",
 StyleBox["spin permutation groups ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "instead of molecular point groups. Consider for example the Hamiltonian of \
three methyl protons in an isotropic solution:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.728220896380918*^9, 3.728221063488654*^9}, {
