   3.8528906545513225`*^9}, {3.8528911943523865`*^9, 3.852891245480312*^9}, {
   3.852892705365851*^9, 3.852892711266095*^9}, {3.852892749410054*^9, 
   3.8528927837296057`*^9}, {3.852892818296978*^9, 3.852892832513153*^9}, {
   3.85289287716869*^9, 3.8528932159268103`*^9}, {3.852893317532903*^9, 
   3.852893412381724*^9}, {3.8528934678402367`*^9, 3.85289355188338*^9}, {
   3.852893590250721*^9, 3.852894318749945*^9}, {3.853156510435047*^9, 
   3.853156557697277*^9}, 
   3.8531565881700845`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"c8c6679b-25a5-41ce-bbe7-\
c901c0095e32"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the quantum context we are typically concerned with evolution of quantum \
states and the transformation of some initial state vector to some final \
state vector. As a result, it is perhaps not too surprising that Lie brackets \
and Lie algebras naturally arise in the description of quantum evolution. \n\n\
For example, the evolution of the density operator is governed by the \
Liouville-von-Neumann equation\n\n",
 StyleBox["d/dt \[Rho](t) = -i [H, \[Rho](t)] \n\n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "where ",
 StyleBox["[H, \[Rho](t)] ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "refers to the commutator between",
 StyleBox[" H",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["\[Rho](t)",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n\n",
 StyleBox["[H, \[Rho](t)] ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " = ",
 StyleBox["H\[Rho](t)-\[Rho](t)H",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n\nObserve that the notation for the commutator (",
 StyleBox["[\[CenterDot],\[CenterDot]]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ") ",
 "is distinct from the notation for the Lie bracket (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[LeftDoubleBracket]", TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"590b81e2-c664-4782-9475-5fb83b78b39d"],
 " \[CenterDot], \[CenterDot]\[RightDoubleBracket]",
 "). T",
 "here are subtle differences between the \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]usual\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] commutator and the Lie bracket, as discussed further \
below. The solution to the Liouville-von-Neumann equation may then be \
expressed as a sum of nested commutators",
 StyleBox["\n\n\[Rho](t) =U(t)\[Rho](0)",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"37fcf1a9-ff94-4a93-aa44-8a9704cf4f1b"],
 StyleBox["(t) = \[Rho](0) + (-i t) [H, \[Rho](0)] + 1/2 ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"-", "i"}], " ", "t"}], ")"}], "2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"97c02521-59ee-4e5b-8676-0a4f2036fbf7"],
 StyleBox[" [H,[H, \[Rho](0)]] + ...\n\n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "Since the density operator is required to remain hermitian at all times, it \
would be nice to know that the r.h.s remains hermitian at all times. For \
example, does the commutator ",
 StyleBox["[X, Y] ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "of two hermitian operators produce a hermitian operator? In other words, \
does the commutator qualify as a Lie bracket taking two hermitian operators \
as an input, returning another hermitian operator?",
 StyleBox["\n\n[\[CenterDot] , \[CenterDot]] :  Herm \[Times] Herm ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   OverscriptBox["\[Rule]", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"?", ")"}]}]], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"89462926-f23c-4873-929c-8922b5a58d37"],
 StyleBox[" Herm\n\n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "The answer is (perhaps surprisingly) no. Instead, the commutator of two \
hermitian operators ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " results in an anti-hermitian operator.\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"[", 
     RowBox[{"X", ",", " ", "Y"}], "]"}], "\[Dagger]"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"f4bed446-7bd7-4cae-a4a0-34bc6220053c"],
 StyleBox[" = ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"XY", "-", "YX"}], ")"}], "\[Dagger]"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"8c8417e6-bcf3-4009-aa07-ab07133c0b9d"],
 StyleBox[" = ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"YX", "-", "XY"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"4fc8782e-a831-4de9-8213-302ed04e8ead"],
 StyleBox[" = ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"-", 
    RowBox[{"[", 
     RowBox[{"X", ",", " ", "Y"}], "]"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"d138fc17-a265-4373-8cd0-804869ad850a"],
 "\n\nHowever, this problem is easily fixed by defining the Lie bracket as \
follows\n\n\[LeftDoubleBracket]",
 StyleBox["X, Y\[RightDoubleBracket] = -i [X,Y] \[Implies] ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"\[LeftDoubleBracket]", 
     RowBox[{"X", ",", "Y"}], "\[RightDoubleBracket]"}], "\[Dagger]"], 
   TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"59b0c057-c909-46a6-ac41-11afce286827"],
 StyleBox[" = ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[LeftDoubleBracket]", 
    RowBox[{"X", ",", "Y"}], "\[RightDoubleBracket]"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"d61738fe-eff8-403a-8e2f-e831c2ebcb0c"],
 "\n\nThe evolution of the density operator may thus be seen to be given by a \
sum of Lie brackets\n\n",
 StyleBox["\[Rho](t) =U(t)\[Rho](0)",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"25c6dd3c-619e-4268-8e8a-e0570ad40fa4"],
 StyleBox["(t) = \[Rho](0) + t \[LeftDoubleBracket]H, \[Rho](0)\
\[RightDoubleBracket] + 1/2 ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}], "2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"bceb8098-717f-42f7-99aa-bf2d6cf4a73f"],
 StyleBox[" \[LeftDoubleBracket]H,\[LeftDoubleBracket]H, \[Rho](0)\
\[RightDoubleBracket]\[RightDoubleBracket] + ...\n\n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "indicating that the r.h.s remains hermitian. This in turn shows that the \
space of density operators forms a Lie algebra with the Lie bracket (strictly \
speaking) not given by the commutator, but instead by a complex commutator\n\n\
\[LeftDoubleBracket]",
 StyleBox["X, Y\[RightDoubleBracket] = -i [X,Y]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.728220896380918*^9, 3.728221063488654*^9}, {
   3.7282211222267337`*^9, 3.728221130577482*^9}, {3.7282211686435347`*^9, 
